    },
    {
      "id": "c19243cde30f0a2730c332830ea178bcdabcd9db",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2015-06-17 15:08:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nFirst problem is this doesn't look optional. Secondly IMNSHO you can't make a one shoe size fits all. For example our Cray systems are running OFED 3.12 stacking using the mlx5 driver which supports FMR. The MLNX 2.04 mlx5 drivers we use on our Power8 nodes don't support FMR plus most likely due to pages being 64K we have to set the map_on_demand to not over flow the pair queues.\nThis is not the case with our Cray OFED 3.12 stack. We have not had the opportunity to try the default mlx5 driver that comes with RHEL7 so I can't say if you need special tweaks.\n\nIn any case I added our admins since their opinions carry more weight than mine.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "17781b19cabfca241f2a064a8912ace22a748863",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2015-06-17 15:09:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "01210d6c04248c55ec4d0e74f443a014f9c35e8c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2015-06-17 18:59:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nJames, what about removing the -mlx5 tunables and just sticking with the -opa tunables for now (default for everything else)?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "699d60578969cf50647b16729f1146d82b6b143b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 301,
        "name": "Dmitry Eremin",
        "email": "dmitry.eremin@intel.com",
        "username": "dmiter",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-06-17 20:40:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nWe or customer can implement more complex logic of tunables selection. mlx5 was get mostly for demonstration. We can remove it now and stay as it was for Mellanox cards.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "0975345be60884b61f3e32b564478c41b7d308e4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2015-06-17 20:52:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nFirst let me discuss this with our admins. I like to know what they think. even with the settings for mlx4 we had to tune the peer_credits down to 63 because our storage backend couldn't keep up with the incoming packets.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "859f176cdcf03da2d2176583d07da29976f39e69",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2015-06-17 21:34:05.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(1 comment)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "99e7ad34ccd52f14e547ab97ab9b84bdead8cf78",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2015-06-17 21:52:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nHas anyone tried this for mixed environments? Say a mlx4/mlx5 system. I don't think this would hold up in that case. Also some questions about what is more important, mlx4 or mlx5. Far more people use mlx4",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "f77c7581f51443bafc2fdb90f52128cb23210171",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 533,
        "name": "John Lewis",
        "email": "lewisj@cray.com",
        "username": "lewisj"
      },
      "date": "2015-06-17 22:26:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> (4 comments)\n > \n > It looks technically OK, but I think it could be improved so it is\n > easier for the admin to know what is happening.\n\n > Has anyone tried this for mixed environments? Say a mlx4/mlx5\n > system. I don't think this would hold up in that case. Also some\n > questions about what is more important, mlx4 or mlx5. Far more\n > people use mlx4\n\n > Has anyone tried this for mixed environments? Say a mlx4/mlx5\n > system. I don't think this would hold up in that case. Also some\n > questions about what is more important, mlx4 or mlx5. Far more\n > people use mlx4\n\n > Has anyone tried this for mixed environments? Say a mlx4/mlx5\n > system. I don't think this would hold up in that case. Also some\n > questions about what is more important, mlx4 or mlx5. Far more\n > people use mlx4\n\nGoing back to Andreas' first comment \"It would be useful to include into the commit comment some (relative?) performance numbers for testing with/without these tunables applied, so that it is clear why this change is being made.\"\n\nI'm exclusively an mlx4/mlx5 user but the defaults given in ko2iblnd.conf appear to create incompatability.  Is it desirable and justifiable to make cards from two vendors (or different cards by the same vendor) explicitly unable to work together in a default configuration?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
